observations.recommendation:
1.1. We recommended, and the Management agreed to strictly adhere to the provisions of COA Circular No. 2020-006 on the one-time cleansing of the PPE account of the Municipality, specifically, the following:
A. IncompletepreparationofRPCPPE per sub-major account group
a. Local Chief Executive (LCE) to temporarily relieve the members of the Inventory Committee to all their regular duties to be able to complete the physical inventory of all PPEs of the LGU as required; and
B. Outdated and incomplete vital information on property stickers
b. Inventory Committee to –
Prepare an updated PIP, and submit the same to the Municipal Mayor to ensure that the conduct of inventory-taking is properly and adequately planned pursuant to COA Circular No. 2020-006;
Submit a copy of the approved PIP to COA at least10calendardaysbeforethescheduledstart of inventory-taking activities;
ConductacompletephysicalcountofPPEbased on the guidelines and procedures provided in COA Circular No. 2020-006 ;
Prepare the RPCPPE, using the prescribed format upon completion of the physical count; and
Update and provide the required information in the property stickers

We recommended, and the Management agreed that:
The MPDC to refrain from describing the PPAs in generic terms in the AIP and that specific PPAs are to be identified during the budget preparation. Also, develop and recommend other procedures to enhance the current practice regarding planning of the 20 percent DF to avoid generic and lump-sum appropriation of projects;
The Municipal Budget Officer to require prior approval or authorization from the SB in case charges are to be made with the lump-sum appropriations either before the release of ARO or certifying the existence of appropriations in the Obligation Request;
The Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to request from SB prior to contract signing by the parties, in case generic terms could not be avoided; and
The Municipal Accountant to ensure that all contracts for projects described in generic terms are supported with an approval or authorization from the SB through SB Resolution which allow the Municipal Mayor, in behalf of the LGU, to enter into contract with the supplier/contractor before certifying the DV.

We recommended, and the Municipal Mayor, Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Engineer agreed to:
Issue demand letters to the contractors by requiring them to submit a catch up plan and compel them to complete the project as soon as possible;
Impose Liquidated Damages pursuant to Annex E of RIRR of RA 9184, if applicable;
Make representation to the NHA to put into writing the reason/s for not downloading the remaining funds and to seek possible remedy such as continuation of the LGU of the housing project using LGU funds so that the structures will not deteriorate further;
Demandfrom thecontractor torepaytheamount of P1.833 million for the unrecouped mobilization, in case the contractor opt not to continue the contract; and
Progress billings are to be deducted with retentionmoneyincaseaccomplishments are50 percentandlessoriftheprojectisnolongeron schedule.

