9. Municipal Treasurer/GSO prepares the SSMI summarizing all the issuances thereof and submit to the Municipal Accountant for recording in the books;

10. Municipal Accountant to recognize issued inventories as expense duly supported by SSMI submitted by the Municipal Treasurer/GSO;

11. Accounting and Treasurer’s Office to maintain SLC and SC, respectively for each item of stocks based on the disbursement vouchers and to regularly update and reconcile their records; and

12. Inventory Committee to conduct the physical count at least twice a year and reconcile the variances with the records with the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant.

We recommended, and Management agreed that:
Thru the Municipal Treasurer to propose an amendment to the Revenue Ordinance to require the submission of annual audited FS and/or monthly, quarterly or annual income tax returns of the preceding taxable year to provide a more reliable basis for assessment of business taxes;
Prior to business renewal period, gather Alphalist of Payees subjected to Expanded Withholding Tax and/or List of Purchases procured by the Municipality and/or Barangays from business establishments registered under their jurisdiction, and upon receipt of business renewal applications, conduct verification and compare the gross sales declared in the sworn statement of business establishments to ensure that the declared gross sales are true and correct;
In case of suspected under declaration of gross sales/receipts, the Municipal Treasurer or his duly authorized representative to conduct audit or examine/assess the books of accounts of the business taxpayers to determine the accurate gross sales or receipts of made which the tax maybe based and to prepare reports on the results of audit or examination of book of accounts;
Direct the BPLO and Municipal Treasurer’s Office to maintain files on sworn statement of gross sales or receipts, audited FS, income tax return, reports on results of audit or examination of accounts, or any evidence to support the declared gross sales or receipts of the business taxpayers; and
Consider imposing sanctions to business establishments in committing false attestation in declaration of gross receipts or sales.

23. To strengthen the risk management capabilities of the LGU and enable it to manage its vulnerabilities in the event of disruptive events, we reiterated our recommendation and Management agreed that the LCE institutionalize the PSCP by creating a working group that will perform the following activities:

a. to conduct risk assessment; 
b. to identify critical processes and functions; 
c. to determine scenarios that may disrupt normal operation; 
d. to conduct risk analysis and impact analysis; 
e. to formulate the PSCP based on the identified risks on critical processes and functions and its related steps to be followed to eliminate, if not mitigate, the impact of the determined disruptions following the prescribed template and be guided by the PSCP guidebook; and
f. to submit plan to the Municipal Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Officer (MDRRMO) for review, to the LCE for approval, and to the SB for the passage of a resolution to institutionalize the PSCP.

24. We also recommended, and Management agreed to improve their monitoring of operational requirements like the submission of PSCP

(1) Municipality’s GFPS to conduct gender mainstreaming through gender audit and gender analysis of its policies, programs, services and the current situation of the LGU in terms of GAD compliance;

 (2) To equip the GFPS with the in-depth knowledge and capacity on GAD, they need to undergo trainings and seminars such as those relating to gender-responsive planning and budgeting, gender analysis, gender audit and the use of various GAD tools for the LGU’s GAD implementation of PAPs; and 

(3) Management to revisit and strictly comply with the provisions of RA No. 9710 and other related provisions of law.

